dataIdInfo.idAbs:
U.S. Telephone Area Code Boundaries represents the telephone area codes for the United States. They are also known as Numbering Plan Areas (NPA). The Numbering Plan Areas reflect current and accurate boundary changes both where new NPAs split from existing NPAs and where new NPAs overlay existing NPAs.

When an NPA is split, the geographic area covered by the old area code is divided geographically, with one portion retaining the previous area code and the other switching to the new area code. When a new NPA is added as an overlay, the old area code remains unaffected. Instead, all or part of the land covered by the old area code is now covered by two area codes.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: U.S. Telephone Area Code Boundaries provides the telephone area codes of the United States for use in telecommunications analysis.

report.measDesc: The dataset is converted to file geodatabase (FGDB) format using tools in ArcGIS. The geometry is checked, and if needed repaired.
After processing, the data set is checked for drawing display and number of records and file sizes compared with source materials.

The horizontal positional accuracy is difficult to determine since the boundaries may follow state, county, city, or other political boundaries. Still other times they may follow streets or other linear features in the database. Since these features are derived from different sources, it is not possible to give a single overall figure for horizontal accuracy.

prcStep.stepDesc: The following steps were performed by Esri: Copied the Area Code (NPA) Boundaries dataset from TomTom Telecommunication Suite v. 2015.06. Attached the fields from Data and Maps 2014 U.S. Telephone Area Code Boundaries. Removed unneeded fields. Converted the dataset into a file geodatabase. For the seven new features, zoomed to each to confirm that it is a duplicate of an existing area code boundary and then calculated its fields STATE and SQMI equal to the existing area code’s values.
